<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

<div class="space-y-6">
<div>
<h3>What foods should you avoid pairing with rosé wine?</h3>
<p>Heavy red meat dishes, strongly flavored game meats, and rich chocolate desserts typically overpower rosé's delicate character. Very spicy foods can make bone-dry rosé taste harsh, while overly salty dishes clash with the wine's fresh fruit character.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>Can rosé wine work with cheese pairings?</h3>
<p>Yes, rosé works excellently with fresh cheeses like goat cheese, mozzarella, and ricotta. Soft-ripened cheeses like brie and camembert also pair well. Avoid aged hard cheeses and blue cheeses, which typically require more substantial red wines.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>How do you choose rosé for outdoor barbecues?</h3>
<p>Select medium-bodied rosé with good acidity for barbecue pairings. Spanish Tempranillo rosé or New World styles work better than delicate Provence wines. The wine needs enough structure to handle grilled flavors and smoky char.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>Does rosé wine work with vegetarian dishes?</h3>
<p>Rosé excels with vegetarian cuisine. Grilled vegetables, pasta primavera, vegetable tarts, and herb-based dishes all create excellent pairings. The wine's fresh character complements vegetables without overwhelming plant-based flavors.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>What's the difference between pairing dry and sweet rosé wines?</h3>
<p>Dry rosé works better with savory dishes, seafood, and Mediterranean cuisine. Sweet rosé complements spicy Asian food, fruit desserts, and brunch dishes. Consider the wine's sweetness level as carefully as you would the food's flavor profile.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>How do you pair rosé with breakfast and brunch foods?</h3>
<p>Rosé works wonderfully with brunch fare. Pair with eggs Benedict, quiche, fruit salads, and pastries. Slightly sweet rosé complements pancakes and French toast, while dry styles work better with savory egg dishes and smoked salmon.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>Can you cook with rosé wine, and does it change pairing options?</h3>
<p>Yes, rosé makes an excellent cooking wine for pan sauces, risottos, and braised dishes. When you cook with rosé, consider serving the same wine with the finished dish to create flavor harmony between the preparation and beverage.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>What seasonal ingredients work best with rosé wine pairings?</h3>
<p>Spring vegetables like asparagus and peas, summer tomatoes and stone fruits, and early fall squash all create natural rosé pairings. The wine's fresh character aligns perfectly with seasonal, locally-sourced ingredients and lighter cooking methods.</p>
